          "body": "The chapter is structured as two parallel panels. Panel One (15:2-18) covers the male: severe/chronic discharge (15:2-15) requiring seven days plus sacrifice, and brief/ordinary discharge — seminal emission (15:16-18) — requiring only washing until evening. Panel Two (15:19-30) covers the female: normal menstruation (15:19-24) creating seven-day impurity, and prolonged/abnormal discharge (15:25-30) requiring seven days of counting after cessation plus sacrifice. The parallelism is exact: the two severe cases (male chronic, female prolonged) receive identical sacrificial resolutions — two birds, one *chattaah*, one *olah*, priestly *kipher* before the LORD (15:15, 30). The symmetry is not accidental; it signals the equal standing of men and women before the purity law. Neither gender is treated as more intrinsically impure than the other; both have conditions that range from mild to severe, and both receive proportionate remedies."
