        "number": 3,
        "title": "The female panel — equal standing, equal remedy",
        "range": "15:19-30",
        "excerpt": "When a woman has a discharge, if her discharge in her body is blood, she shall continue in her menstrual impurity for seven days… So the priest shall make atonement on her behalf before the LORD because of her impure discharge.",
        "body": "The female panel of the chapter (15:19-30) is structurally identical to the male panel — and that structural identity is itself a theological statement. In a world where many ancient Near Eastern purity systems treated female impurity as fundamentally more severe or more defiling than male impurity, Leviticus 15 grants exact parallel treatment. The woman with prolonged discharge (15:25-30) receives the same restoration protocol as the man with chronic discharge (15:2-15): seven days of counting, washing, eighth-day sacrifice, priestly atonement. The sacrificial formula in 15:30 is verbatim from 15:15. Women stand before the purity law in full symmetry with men.\n\nThe *niddah* (15:19, 20, 24, 25, 26) — the technical term for menstrual impurity — creates a seven-day state of uncleanness that extends to objects and persons who contact the woman during this period. The man who lies with her during her *niddah* (15:24) absorbs the full seven days of her impurity. This regulation is not a punishment for marital intimacy; it is a statement that the most intimate physical contact is also the most thorough transmission of cultic status. The text of Leviticus 18:19 and 20:18 treat deliberate violation of the *niddah* boundary with increasing severity — but the regulation itself in chapter 15 is descriptive and restorative, not punitive.\n\nThe woman with the prolonged, abnormal discharge (15:25-30) is the most vivid connection to the New Testament. In Mark 5:25-34 and Luke 8:43-48, a woman who 'had had a hemorrhage for twelve years' — whose condition would have made her continuously in the state described in Leviticus 15:25 for over a decade — presses through the crowd and touches the hem of Jesus's garment. Under the regulations of Leviticus 15, this touch would have transferred her impurity to Jesus. Instead, the reverse happens: power goes out from Him, and she is healed. Jesus does not become ritually impure; the woman becomes clean. This is not an incidental detail; it is a confrontation with the entire system of Leviticus 15. The one who touches Jesus is not contaminating Him; she is encountering the living water that cleanses the most severe impurity — and the healing is immediate, total, and requires no seven days of waiting, no eighth-day sacrifice, no priestly atonement. The priest is already present.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Niddah* comes from a root meaning to remove or be cast away — *niddah* is the removed one, she who is temporarily set apart. The same word in later Hebrew came to mean 'menstruation.' *Mishkav* (bed) and *keli* (vessel, furniture, object) are the two categories of objects that become secondarily impure in both panels — the parallelism of vocabulary reinforces the structural parallelism of the two panels."
