      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The theological summary — holiness, death, and the indwelling God",
        "range": "15:31-33",
        "excerpt": "Thus you shall keep the sons of Israel separated from their uncleanness, so that they will not die in their uncleanness by their defiling My tabernacle that is among them.",
        "body": "Verse 31 is the chapter's hermeneutical key and one of the most compressed and powerful statements in the entire Pentateuch. Three things converge in a single sentence: the law's purpose, the consequence of its violation, and the reason everything matters.\n\nThe **purpose** is expressed with the verb *nazar* — 'you shall keep them separated.' The hiphil form of *nazar* (to consecrate, to separate, to set apart) appears here uniquely applied to separation from impurity. The same root generates the word *nazir* (Nazirite) — the person set apart to God by a special vow. The structural echo is significant: Israel's separation from impurity is a form of consecration to the holy God who dwells among them.\n\nThe **consequence** of failure is stated starkly: 'they will not die in their uncleanness.' Death is the outcome of a holy God's presence meeting unchecked defilement. This is not a ceremonial penalty; it is an ontological one. The living, holy God and accumulated human impurity cannot coexist in the same space without catastrophic result. Leviticus 10 has already demonstrated this: Aaron's sons Nadab and Abihu approached the holy with 'strange fire' and were consumed. The purity laws are protective, not punitive — they exist so that Israel can survive the nearness of the God they need.\n\nThe **reason** is the phrase that anchors everything: *mishkani asher betokham* — 'My tabernacle that is among them.' The LORD speaks of the sanctuary in the first-person possessive: *My* tabernacle. And He locates it *among them* — *betokham*, in their midst, in the center of the camp. The entire elaborate system of Leviticus 15 exists to preserve that indwelling. God desires to be near His people; the purity laws make that nearness survivable. They are not walls to keep Israel away from God but buffers to keep God's holy presence from consuming an impure people.\n\nCalvin (*Commentaries on the Four Last Books of Moses*, on Leviticus 15) correctly identifies the chapter's ultimate direction: the laws teach Israel that they need a mediator, that their own bodies in their present condition cannot stand before the holy God without help. The priest, the blood, the running water, the counted days — all of it is pedagogical. It teaches what the body needs, what God requires, and that provision has been made. The New Testament completes the pedagogy: the high priest who makes atonement on the eighth day is Himself the living water, the sinless flesh, and the blood that cleanses from all impurity — permanently, not until evening.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nazar* (to keep separate, to consecrate) in the hiphil here has the force of 'you shall cause them to be separated' — Moses and Aaron are the agents of Israel's separation from impurity, just as they have been its instructors throughout the chapter. *Mishkani* (My tabernacle) is the first-person possessive singular — the LORD speaks of His own dwelling; the stakes of defilement are therefore personal to Him, not merely institutional."
      }
